==================================================
RESPONSIVE AND LAYOUT SYSTEM RULES
==================================================

All layouts must be built mobile-first.

The whole project must use one consistent responsive system.
Do not create different container widths, spacing logic, or breakpoint logic from section to section unless explicitly instructed.

==================================================
CONTAINER RULES
==================================================

Use a shared container system across the entire website.

Every section must follow the same structural pattern:
- section wrapper
- inner container
- section content/grid

Use one main container class system consistently.

Recommended structure:
- .container
- .container--wide
- .container--narrow
- .container--full only when explicitly needed

Default behavior:
- container width: 100%
- container max-width should be controlled globally
- container side padding must adapt per viewport
- content should never touch screen edges on tablet or mobile

Use a global container system like this:
- desktop max-width: 1200px to 1320px
- wide container: 1400px if truly needed
- narrow container: 900px to 1000px for text-heavy sections
- mobile/tablet side padding must be consistent across all sections

Never hardcode random widths per section.
Never create one section with one container logic and another section with a different one.
The same container principles must be used everywhere.

==================================================
RESPONSIVE SPACING RULES
==================================================

Use a consistent spacing scale across the whole project.

Do not hardcode random pixel spacing values independently inside sections.
Use shared spacing tokens, SCSS variables, functions, or mixins.

Spacing must be fluid and scalable.
Prefer:
- clamp() for section padding, margins, and typography
- percentages
- max-width
- gap
- flex and grid
- minmax()
- width: 100%

Avoid fixed layout values when fluid values are more appropriate.

Section spacing must feel visually consistent across the whole site.
Do not make one section very tight and another overly spacious without a clear reason.

All sections should use the same vertical rhythm.

==================================================
TYPOGRAPHY RESPONSIVE RULES
==================================================

Typography must scale fluidly across viewport sizes.

Do not use rigid font sizes everywhere.
Prefer clamp() for:
- hero titles
- section titles
- body text when appropriate
- buttons if needed

Typography hierarchy must stay consistent across all pages and sections.
Do not create random heading sizes from section to section.

Use a shared type scale:
- hero title
- section title
- subsection title
- body text
- small text

All must be controlled centrally.

==================================================
LAYOUT RULES
==================================================

Build layouts so they naturally adapt across:
- mobile
- tablet
- laptop
- desktop

Do not rely on fixed heights.
Do not rely on fixed card widths unless strictly necessary.
Do not use hardcoded positioning if the same result can be achieved with flex or grid.

Use:
- CSS Grid for section layouts, cards, and complex alignment
- Flexbox for smaller alignment patterns
- gap instead of margin hacks wherever possible

Prefer layouts like:
- grid-template-columns with repeat()
- minmax()
- auto-fit
- auto-fill when appropriate

On smaller screens:
- stacks should become single-column when needed
- text should remain readable
- buttons should remain tappable
- spacing should stay balanced
- media should scale proportionally

==================================================
IMAGE AND MEDIA RESPONSIVE RULES
==================================================

All images and media must be responsive by default.

Use:
- max-width: 100%
- height: auto

Avoid fixed image dimensions in layout unless required by design.
If a ratio is needed, use aspect-ratio consistently.
Use object-fit only when truly needed.

Images must not overflow containers.
Media blocks must align with the shared container system.

==================================================
CONSISTENCY RULES FOR ALL SECTIONS
==================================================

Every section must feel like part of the same design system.

Do not generate:
- one section with oversized padding and another with tiny padding
- one section with a different container width
- one section with random breakpoint behavior
- one section using fixed px widths while another uses fluid logic

All sections must follow the same responsive logic, same spacing system, same container behavior, and same typography scale.

If a new section is added, it must inherit the same layout rules as the rest of the project.

==================================================
BREAKPOINT RULES
==================================================

Use one shared breakpoint system across the whole project.
Do not invent breakpoints per section.

Use centralized SCSS breakpoint variables/mixins.

Example breakpoint logic:
- xs: 480px
- sm: 576px
- md: 768px
- lg: 1024px
- xl: 1280px
- xxl: 1440px

All responsive changes must use the shared breakpoint system only.

==================================================
DEVELOPMENT RULES FOR RESPONSIVE OUTPUT
==================================================

When building any section:
- first think mobile
- then tablet
- then desktop
- preserve readability and spacing at every size
- keep structure scalable
- avoid hardcoded widths/heights unless absolutely necessary
- use shared containers and spacing tokens
- keep visual consistency with the rest of the website

The final result must look structured, balanced, and consistent on desktop, tablet, and mobile.


==================================================
SCSS AUTHORING STYLE RULES
==================================================

Write real SCSS, not plain CSS inside .scss files.

Use SCSS nesting consistently with BEM.

Correct style:
- keep the block as the top-level selector
- nest elements inside the block using &
- nest modifiers using &
- nest pseudo-classes and pseudo-elements inside the related selector
- keep nesting clean and readable
- avoid unnecessary repetition of the full selector name

Use this pattern:
.block {
    ...

    &__element {
        ...

        &:hover,
        &:focus {
            ...
        }
    }

    &--modifier {
        ...
    }
}

Do not write SCSS like plain CSS with repeated selectors such as:
.block {}
.block__element {}
.block__element a {}
.block__element a:hover {}

Instead, group related styles inside the parent block whenever they belong to the same component.

SCSS should feel modular, organized, and truly nested, while still staying readable and not becoming overly deep.

Use nested SCSS structure by default.
Do not output flat CSS-style selector repetition inside SCSS files unless there is a very specific reason.


==================================================
SHARED LAYOUT ABSTRACTION RULES
==================================================

Do not repeat shared layout declarations across section files.

If the same layout pattern appears more than once, extract it into a reusable global abstraction.

Shared patterns such as:
- container widths
- horizontal paddings
- section max-width wrappers
- flex alignment utilities
- grid wrappers
- vertical section spacing

must not be rewritten inside every section partial.

These shared patterns must be centralized in:
- SCSS variables
- SCSS mixins
- SCSS placeholders if appropriate
- global layout partials

A global container system must exist and be reused everywhere.

Do not redefine .container inside individual section files unless there is a very specific exception.
Instead:
- define .container globally once
- define modifiers like .container--wide or .container--narrow globally if needed
- let section files style only their own block and inner elements

If a section needs layout behavior inside the container, use a section-specific inner wrapper such as:
- .hero__inner
- .header__inner
- .about__inner

Do not put section-specific flex or grid layout rules directly on .container if that would affect shared behavior.

If the same SCSS declarations appear in multiple files, extract them into a shared mixin or global utility instead of duplicating them.



